properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A drastic change in conditions is expected for southern Alberta on Friday. An approaching weather system is expected to bring a dramatic change to weather conditions in southern Alberta. In the Calgary, Brooks, Lethbridge, Medicine Hat, Okotoks, and Cypress Hills areas temperatures will start out well above freezing with widely scattered showers. However the cold front with this system will bring gusty northerly winds to 80 km/h and a sharp drop in temperatures. The front may also bring heavier pockets of snow and blowing snow as well. This abrupt change in weather will lead to hazardous travel conditions, and may occur during the Friday afternoon commute. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The first significant snowfall of the season is possible this weekend. An intensifying area of low pressure from the Upper Midwestern United States is expected to bring widespread snowfall. Snow will begin in Northwestern Ontario on Saturday afternoon before reaching the Geraldton area by Saturday evening. Locations near to Lake Superior may receive rain mixed with snow thus limiting snowfall amounts. There remains considerable uncertainty as to the exact track of the system, however, snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are possible by the time the snow ends on Sunday. Snowfall Warnings may be required as the event draws nearer. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A moisture-laden Pacific front has made landfall onto the central coast of B.C. Heavy rain will continue this morning before the front exits the region. This system has produced close to 100 mm of rain over coastal regions and around 50 mm over inland areas last night. Additional 10 to 15 mm can be expected this morning before the rain tapers off. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system will track across southwestern Saskatchewan today bringing accumulating snow to areas south of a line from roughly Kindersley to Oxbow. The snow will move into western regions this morning, central areas this afternoon, and eastern areas this evening. In some places the precipitation may initially be mixed with rain, but for the most part it will fall as snow - except in the extreme southwest corner of the province where more of a mixture is expected. Total snowfall accumulations will be in the 5 to 10 cm range in a number of areas. Current indications are that the highest amounts will fall from about Piapot through Shaunavon to Rockglen as well as along the northern slopes of the Cypress Hills. The system will track quickly out of the region tonight, but before departing will bring strong gusty northerly winds to the southwest corner of the province during the evening. By Saturday a much cooler air mass will be over the area with temperatures well below seasonal values. Please be aware that roads may become slippery along with reduced visibility at times. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls may develop late this morning and into this afternoon along an intense cold front moving southward across southern Alberta. This cold front is expected to produce brief periods of intense snowfall and reduced visibilities. The risk for snow squalls will diminish early this evening as the front pushes into Montana. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
